11:20.200 --> 11:23.900
                        Hot dog!

11:23.900 --> 11:26.100
                 Care to help me
                 with my pants? 

11:26.200 --> 11:28.300
            ( <i>happy humming</i> )   

11:34.200 --> 11:36.300
    Carla? It's your church.    

11:36.400 --> 11:38.000
             Would you tell them
             we're on our way.  

11:38.000 --> 11:39.800
     Well, that's just it.      
     They had to go ahead       

11:39.800 --> 11:41.800
     with the other wedding     
    and cancel yours.           

11:41.900 --> 11:43.500
    I knew it.                  

11:43.500 --> 11:44.700
    I <i>knew</i> it!                  

11:58.300 --> 12:01.300
     You're out of uniform.     

12:10.400 --> 12:13.000
        MONSIGNOR:              
     Dear friends, you have     
        come together...        

12:13.100 --> 12:15.000
CLIFF:                          
It sure was nice                
of the Monsignor                

12:15.100 --> 12:17.100
to let Carla and Eddie          
get married here                

12:17.200 --> 12:19.300
in the rectory chapel.          

12:19.300 --> 12:21.700
             NORM:              
Yeah, it was kind of nice       
             of us              

12:21.700 --> 12:24.700
to buy all those raffle tickets,
              too.              

12:24.700 --> 12:26.900
            FRASIER:            
        Good Lord,              
     it's crowded in here.      

12:27.000 --> 12:28.300
    But on the upside,          

12:28.300 --> 12:32.000
it does satiate any desire      
I might have had to visit Tokyo.

12:33.400 --> 12:37.100
Edward, have you come here      
freely without reservation      

12:37.100 --> 12:40.200
        to give yourself        
     to Carla in marriage?      

12:40.200 --> 12:41.800
            Edward?             

12:41.900 --> 12:45.500
     Carla, where's Edward?     

12:45.500 --> 12:49.700
     Carla? Where's Carla?      

12:49.800 --> 12:52.200
Excuse me.                      
Excuse me!                      

12:52.300 --> 12:54.100
    Lady with a baby.           

12:54.100 --> 12:58.200
        Excuse...               
  Would you get off the dress!  

12:58.200 --> 12:59.700
     All right, all right,      
        all right.              

12:59.700 --> 13:01.200
      Crank it up, Father.      

13:01.300 --> 13:04.700
All the forces in the universe  
say we have to be done by 4:00. 

13:04.800 --> 13:06.100
         ( <i>bell tolls</i> )         
            Oh, no!             

13:06.200 --> 13:08.200
    Do you, Edward Raymond,     
  take Carla Maria Victoria...  

13:08.200 --> 13:09.200
  Hurry! Hurry! Please, hurry!  

13:09.200 --> 13:12.400
 Angelina Theresa Apollonia...  

13:12.400 --> 13:14.100
             CARLA:             
            Oh, rat!            

13:14.100 --> 13:17.500
    Why couldn't my parents     
      have named me Judy?       

13:21.900 --> 13:24.100
            Go on, go on, go on.

13:30.500 --> 13:32.300
Hey, here they come!            

13:32.300 --> 13:33.400
     Ladies and gentlemen,      

13:33.400 --> 13:35.700
    this is the moment          
  we've all been waiting for.   

13:35.800 --> 13:39.300
  Appearing for the first time  
  anywhere, the happy couple,   

13:39.400 --> 13:41.300
Mr. and Mrs. Eddie LeBec.       

13:41.400 --> 13:43.200
         ( <i>drum roll</i> )          

13:43.200 --> 13:44.900
( <i>cheering and applause</i> )       

13:47.100 --> 13:49.900
        That's a keeper.        

13:50.000 --> 13:51.700
            Hey, guys, it's     
            your wedding day.   

13:51.700 --> 13:53.400
            Show a little teeth 
            here, all right?    

13:53.500 --> 13:54.900
        I can't, Sammy.         

13:55.000 --> 13:57.800
    We were pronounced          
     man and wife at 4:01.      

13:57.900 --> 14:00.200
        We might as well have   
        been pronounced dead.   

14:00.300 --> 14:01.200
                We're doomed.   

14:01.300 --> 14:03.400
                Music, music!   

14:03.400 --> 14:04.600
     Aw, come on, you guys.     

14:04.600 --> 14:05.600
        Think about all         
    the wedding gifts           

14:05.600 --> 14:06.800
        you got to open         
          over there.           

14:06.800 --> 14:07.800
                Yeah.           

14:07.900 --> 14:08.800
                I guess I should
                be grateful     

14:08.900 --> 14:10.000
        Eddy didn't fall down   
        the church steps        

14:10.100 --> 14:11.200
            and break his leg.  

14:11.200 --> 14:12.900
            How is it, anyway?  

14:12.900 --> 14:16.500
I think I just                  
wrenched it a little.           

14:16.500 --> 14:19.500
                They don't look 
                too happy to me.

14:19.600 --> 14:22.900
No. They do look married,       
though.                         

14:26.300 --> 14:29.200
What's that                     
ugly-looking thing?             

14:29.200 --> 14:31.600
        It's not an ugly thing. 

14:31.600 --> 14:34.000
                It's a Wabby.   

14:34.000 --> 14:38.600
What's a Wabby, Webecca?        

14:38.700 --> 14:41.700
        It's a "Women of Boston 
        Business" award.        

14:41.700 --> 14:43.300
        I'm very proud of it.   

14:43.400 --> 14:46.000
            It happens to be    
            very prestigious.   

14:46.000 --> 14:48.700
            Thousands of women  
            have won it.        

14:48.700 --> 14:51.400
What's it doing                 
out here?                       

14:51.400 --> 14:53.600
You trying                      
to impress your boss?           

14:53.600 --> 14:54.700
                I'm glad        
                you reminded me.

14:54.800 --> 14:56.500
        I'm completely          
        forgot he was coming.   

14:56.500 --> 14:57.500
Yeah, sure you did.             

14:57.500 --> 14:58.500
Hey, you know,                  

14:58.600 --> 15:01.200
every time Evan Drake's name    
gets mentioned                  

15:01.300 --> 15:03.100
you get a little red            
around the gills.               

15:03.100 --> 15:05.000
Do you have                     
a crush on him                  
or something?                   

15:05.000 --> 15:06.600
            I beg your pardon.  

15:06.700 --> 15:09.400
                He happens to be
                a married man.  

15:09.400 --> 15:11.800
        Although not happily.   

15:13.500 --> 15:16.000
Oh, you <i>do</i> have a crush on him. 

15:16.000 --> 15:17.600
        How cute!               

15:17.600 --> 15:19.600
"Oh, Evan, Evan."               

15:23.200 --> 15:25.000
Great stuffed mushrooms,        
Cliffie.                        

15:25.000 --> 15:26.100
                Try the Swedish 
                meatballs.      

15:26.100 --> 15:27.800
                They're out     
                of this world.  

15:27.800 --> 15:28.900
        Yeah.                   

15:28.900 --> 15:32.300
Ooh, try 'em together!          
Together!                       

15:32.300 --> 15:34.000
     Excuse me, gentlemen.      

15:34.000 --> 15:35.200
     Do you plan on leaving     

15:35.200 --> 15:37.100
    any hors d'oeuvres          
        for latecomers?         

15:37.100 --> 15:39.100
        Hey, you snooze,        
        you lose.               

15:40.700 --> 15:42.000
Ooh-ooh! Rumaki!                

15:42.100 --> 15:43.500
Come on.                        

15:47.500 --> 15:49.400
    And now it's time           
for the traditional first dance,

15:49.400 --> 15:51.200
  and we all know who's going   
          to start it.          

15:53.300 --> 15:56.600
 Holy cow, it isn't me, is it?  

15:57.900 --> 15:59.100
Let's welcome                   

15:59.200 --> 16:02.800
the happy couple Carla and Eddie
to the dance floor.             

16:05.300 --> 16:10.300
      ¶ The greatest love       
    the world has known... ¶    

16:15.800 --> 16:18.100
Hit me again, Harley.           

16:18.100 --> 16:20.900
    Third time's the charm.     

16:25.100 --> 16:29.300
            So, uh, where's your
            big-shot lover boy? 

16:29.400 --> 16:32.900
A: I told you                   
he is not my lover boy.         

16:33.000 --> 16:38.400
B: The big shot SOB             
is in a meeting.                

16:38.500 --> 16:41.100
C: Choke on it.                 

16:41.200 --> 16:42.300
     There's a happy pair.      

16:42.300 --> 16:43.500
    Say cheeseburger.           

16:43.500 --> 16:45.400
                    Uh, no, no. 

16:45.400 --> 16:47.600
        All right,              
      that was a good one,      

16:47.600 --> 16:50.700
even with Miss Howe's eyes      
     kinda gimpy like that.     

16:51.900 --> 16:52.800
                Oh, Norm, look. 

16:52.800 --> 16:54.700
            We forgot about     
            the dessert table.  

16:54.800 --> 16:56.300
        And we call ourselves   
        guests.                 

16:58.300 --> 17:01.300
            Ma, you want        
            to trade partners?  

17:01.300 --> 17:03.900
            Why not?            
            I'm going to die.   

17:03.900 --> 17:08.200
            I'm going to dance  
            with my mother,     
            all right?          

17:10.200 --> 17:12.500
                How about a cup 
                of coffee, huh? 

17:12.500 --> 17:14.300
      Why would I do that?      

17:14.300 --> 17:15.599
    Well, because I've seen     

17:15.700 --> 17:18.500
      a lot of ladies hit       
the champagne in my time.       

17:18.599 --> 17:20.500
                One minute      
                they're doing   
                just fine.      

17:20.500 --> 17:22.900
            The next minute     
            it kind of sneaks   
            up on them          

17:22.900 --> 17:24.800
            and they're doing   
            all sorts           

17:24.800 --> 17:26.500
      of wild and crazy...      

17:26.500 --> 17:30.100
  Why <i>am</i> I giving you coffee?   

17:31.200 --> 17:33.400
                    So, Eddie,  

17:33.500 --> 17:36.800
        what's Mother Tortelli  
        like in bed?            

17:47.300 --> 17:50.100
                    What are you
                    looking at, 
                    pretty lady?

17:50.100 --> 17:52.600
I'm looking at you.             

17:52.600 --> 17:55.100
            Well, I'm looking   
            back at you.        

17:55.100 --> 17:57.600
I think I'm beginning           
to see you                      

17:57.700 --> 17:59.500
in a whole new light.           

17:59.600 --> 18:02.800
        Why don't you tell me   
        what you see?           

18:04.200 --> 18:07.200
You have a really weird face.   

18:10.200 --> 18:12.700
Your eyebrows                   
are growing together            

18:12.800 --> 18:15.500
like a big old                  
ugly caterpillar.               

18:17.000 --> 18:20.700
Oh, look,                       
they're cutting the cake.       

18:45.100 --> 18:47.400
And now as the hour draws late, 

18:47.500 --> 18:49.900
    it's time for the bride     
     to throw the bouquet.      

18:49.900 --> 18:51.800
    Okay, come on, come on,     
        everybody.              

18:53.700 --> 18:55.300
                You all ready?  

18:55.400 --> 18:59.000
                Okay, heads up, 
                you old maids.  

18:59.000 --> 19:02.300
        Dr. Crane,              
        a girl's supposed       
        to catch the bouquet.   

19:02.400 --> 19:03.900
Well, then the girls            
should have been                

19:03.900 --> 19:05.100
a little bit quicker.           

19:05.100 --> 19:07.000
                Here, knock     
                yourself out.   

19:14.300 --> 19:17.400
    I think it's time           
     for me to pack it in.      

19:17.400 --> 19:18.200
Uh, you know,                   
I don't think                   

19:18.200 --> 19:19.600
you're in any condition         
to drive, Miss Howe.            

19:19.600 --> 19:20.800
Let me give you                 
a lift home, all right?         

19:20.900 --> 19:22.000
         I don't know.          

19:22.000 --> 19:26.100
 I've never been alone in a car 
     with such a hairy guy.     

19:27.400 --> 19:30.600
    Are you sure you weren't    
    in <i>The Planet of The Apes?</i>  

19:31.500 --> 19:34.900
            Can anybody else    
            please take me home?

19:35.000 --> 19:37.100
There's room in our car.        

19:37.100 --> 19:38.600
You can sit on my lap.          

19:38.600 --> 19:41.100
                Darling, you're 
                married now.    

19:41.100 --> 19:43.700
                You don't have  
                a lap.          

19:43.800 --> 19:46.900
Come on.                        
You think I'm so ugly?          

19:46.900 --> 19:48.300
I'll let you get a bag          

19:48.300 --> 19:50.400
and put it over my head,        
all right?                      

19:50.400 --> 19:53.400
         Just a minute.         
    Let me get my bag.          

19:53.500 --> 19:55.700
        And yours.              

19:55.700 --> 19:59.400
         I'm not crazy          
about the way that girl flirts. 

19:59.400 --> 20:00.700
And now, folks,                 

20:00.700 --> 20:02.000
 as the lucky couple gets ready 

20:02.000 --> 20:03.500
        to embark               
  on their new life together,   

20:03.500 --> 20:07.000
let's all throw some rice,      
    the symbol of fertility.    

20:08.800 --> 20:10.300
                    Ow!         

20:10.400 --> 20:12.400
                        Oh, ow! 

20:12.500 --> 20:13.600
                    Ah!         

20:13.600 --> 20:14.900
I can't go                      
out here, Eddie.                

20:14.900 --> 20:15.900
                            Why?

20:16.000 --> 20:17.000
No, it's too dangerous.         

20:17.100 --> 20:18.100
                    I'm okay.   

20:18.100 --> 20:19.700
Who are we trying               
to kid here?                    

20:19.700 --> 20:22.600
We're living                    
in the shadow                   
of the curse                    

20:22.600 --> 20:24.200
we brought                      
on ourselves.                   

20:24.300 --> 20:26.000
I can't go on                   
with this.                      

20:26.000 --> 20:27.000
                Come on, Carla. 

20:27.000 --> 20:28.000
          No, no, no.           

20:28.000 --> 20:30.800
                I think maybe   
                we should get   
                an annulment.   

20:30.900 --> 20:33.200
            Oh, would you two   
            stop it?!           

20:33.200 --> 20:34.200
    I can't believe...          

20:34.200 --> 20:36.300
  This should be the happiest   
    day of your lives,          

20:36.400 --> 20:38.500
      and all you've done       
    is moan and groan           

20:38.600 --> 20:40.400
                all day long.   
                I mean, come on.

20:40.400 --> 20:41.600
  It's one thing to play along  

20:41.600 --> 20:44.200
  with this superstition stuff  
  for, you know, for some fun,  

20:44.300 --> 20:45.700
     but you're letting it      
        interfere               

20:45.800 --> 20:47.300
with your happiness here.       

20:47.300 --> 20:48.200
                You two         
                are wonderful.  

20:48.300 --> 20:49.600
            You got everything  
            in your life        

20:49.600 --> 20:51.000
            to look forward to. 

20:51.000 --> 20:53.200
    Please, please, come on.    
        Trust me.               

20:53.200 --> 20:55.700
Nothing bad is going to happen. 

20:55.700 --> 20:58.200
        ( <i>phone rings</i> )         

20:58.200 --> 21:00.500
    You got my personal word    
            on that.            

21:00.500 --> 21:02.500
I mean, superstition,           
it's for the birds.             

21:02.600 --> 21:04.300
Just go on                      
with your normal life.          

21:04.300 --> 21:06.000
Woody, do you mind?             

21:06.000 --> 21:07.100
All right, fine.                
Go ahead. Answer it.            

21:07.100 --> 21:08.300
It's probably                   
just somebody who wants         

21:08.300 --> 21:10.700
to, uh, know what time          
the bar closes.                 

21:10.700 --> 21:12.900
            We close at 2:00.   

21:14.300 --> 21:15.700
            Eddie, it's for you.

21:15.700 --> 21:17.500
                Some guy        
                from the Bruins.

21:17.500 --> 21:18.600
Maybe, maybe you oughta...      

21:18.700 --> 21:21.800
Probably just want              
to congratulate me              
on my wedding.                  

21:21.900 --> 21:23.700
Yeah, right.                    
That's it. That's it.           

21:23.700 --> 21:25.900
        Hello.                  

21:25.900 --> 21:27.100
        Oh, hiya, Frank         

21:27.200 --> 21:28.600
     Yeah, how's it going?      

21:28.600 --> 21:29.500
It's Frank.                     

21:29.500 --> 21:30.800
Yeah,                           

21:30.800 --> 21:33.000
            uh-huh.             

21:33.100 --> 21:34.200
            Uh-huh.             

21:35.500 --> 21:38.000
            Uh-huh.             

21:38.000 --> 21:39.900
Okay, yeah.                     

21:39.900 --> 21:43.400
Yeah, thanks a lot.             

21:43.400 --> 21:45.200
Good-bye, Frank.                

21:47.200 --> 21:49.400
Do I smell a bonus?             

21:49.500 --> 21:51.800
They cut me from the team.      

21:51.800 --> 21:53.700
They're going                   
with the youth movement.        

21:53.700 --> 21:57.500
They tried to trade me,         
but nobody wanted me.           

21:57.500 --> 21:58.600
    I'm sorry, Carla.           

21:58.600 --> 22:00.400
            I guess             
     all the superstitions      

22:00.500 --> 22:02.200
    finally caught up           
            with us.            

22:03.200 --> 22:05.100
Wait a minute.                  
Wait a minute.                  

22:05.100 --> 22:09.300
I can blame a lot               
of things on superstition,      

22:09.400 --> 22:11.800
but you aren't                  
the greatest goalie             
in the world, honey.            

22:11.800 --> 22:14.100
            What are you saying 
            to me, Carla?       

22:14.200 --> 22:17.100
Well, you know,                 
the end of last year            
you were losing it,             

22:17.100 --> 22:19.900
and now you're older,           
and your reflexes are shot.     

22:19.900 --> 22:21.700
            Oh, thanks a lot.   

22:21.700 --> 22:25.500
            I'm feeling a lot   
            better already.     

22:25.600 --> 22:29.900
And if that wasn't              
because of superstition,        

22:29.900 --> 22:34.000
then maybe the twins            
aren't bad luck either.         

22:34.100 --> 22:36.100
Could it be possible            

22:36.200 --> 22:39.500
that I'm just having twins      
    because the eggs split?     

22:42.500 --> 22:43.600
          Whoa, whoa!           

22:43.600 --> 22:48.700
 And maybe your mother hates me 
     because she's stupid.      

22:50.400 --> 22:51.800
     And Anthony hates you      

22:51.900 --> 22:55.500
     because he takes after     
 his no-good rat-faced father.  

22:57.000 --> 23:00.100
      And all those things      
 that we thought were bad luck  

23:00.200 --> 23:03.200
    had nothing to do           
    with superstition.          

23:03.200 --> 23:05.000
         It was just...         

23:05.100 --> 23:07.100
             life.              

23:08.500 --> 23:11.700
         Unfortunately,         
it happens to be my life.       

23:12.900 --> 23:16.300
         What the heck?         

23:16.300 --> 23:20.200
    I'm married and in love     
    with a great guy.           

23:23.800 --> 23:27.200
So, I guess                     
that evens things up.           

23:27.200 --> 23:28.800
No, it doesn't.                 

23:30.100 --> 23:33.400
But it makes life worth living. 

23:33.400 --> 23:34.600
        No, it doesn't.         

23:36.600 --> 23:39.400
But it's something.             

23:39.400 --> 23:42.800
    So let's get on with it.    

23:42.800 --> 23:44.500
What do you say,                
hubby?                          

23:46.900 --> 23:50.200
        I say let's get on      
        with the honeymoon, eh? 

23:50.300 --> 23:51.400
See you at 2:00 A.M.            

23:51.500 --> 23:54.700
Somebody's got to work          
in this family.                 

23:54.700 --> 23:57.700
Hi. I'm Mrs. Eddie LeBec.       

23:57.800 --> 23:59.500
What'll you have?               

